        "body": "The draft dust settles in D.C., and Adam Peters just flipped the script on a 5-12 squad that limped to third in the NFC East - trading for Laremy Tunsil left them with six picks, but they loaded up offense with four gems instead of bulking the defense everyone craved. <strong>Sonny Styles</strong>, the safety snagged early, headlines alongside receiver Antonio Williams, whose slot-ready hands could stretch Dan Quinn's scheme wide open; Joshua Josephs in the fifth bolsters the edge with free agents looming. UDFAs are trickling in quietly, plugging depth holes without fanfare. This haul - balanced, not flashy - fits Quinn's revamp like a glove, shoving Williams into a WR room begging for juice after last year's drought. Styles might crack the secondary Day 1, his range patching gaps exposed in that six-games-back finish. No more excuses; Peters maximized value, passing on corners like Mansoor Delane to Chiefs thieves. <strong>Watch OTAs for Williams' first snaps - they'll signal if this class ignites a playoff push or just teases one.</strong>",
